h5. Problem Definition
At the moment, there seems to be inconsistency when running JQL with negation in JQL format and when it is saved as filter. For example:
FEV - filter 1: {{project = TEST AND status = Closed}}
FEV - filter 2: {{project = TEST AND status was not in ("In Progress")}}

Running this JQL query will result in correct list of issues:
{{filter = "FEV - filter 1" AND filter not in ("FEV - filter 2")}}

However, when you save the above JQL as a filter, and access the filter, it results in error:
!jql.png|thumbnail!

h5. Suggested Solution
Even though the JQL can be constructed in a simpler way, issue navigator should be consistent in giving the result when the same JQL query is being run as JQL and as filter.

h3. Problem Definition

When we want to search issues which does not contain some word (e.g. xxx) in a text field (including issues which don't have any value in the field), we're supposed to use the following JQL.

{code}
<FIELD_NAME> !~ "xxx" or <FIELD_NAME> is empty
{code}

However, it is difficult for our customers to know the behavior from [our documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiracoreserver073/advanced-searching-operators-reference-861257221.html?#Advancedsearching-operatorsreference-DOES_NOT_CONTAINDOESNOTCONTAIN:!~] and some customers assume that the JQL should be without {{is empty}} as follows.

{code}
<FIELD_NAME> !~ "xxx"
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution

The similar thing happens when using {{NOT IN}} operator but a valid example is documented [there|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiracoreserver073/advanced-searching-operators-reference-861257221.html#Advancedsearching-operatorsreference-NOT_INNOTIN] as follows.

{code}
FixVersion not in (A, B, C, D) or FixVersion is empty
{code}

It would be better if {{DOES NOT CONTAIN}} operator has such a good example in [the document|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiracoreserver073/advanced-searching-operators-reference-861257221.html?#Advancedsearching-operatorsreference-DOES_NOT_CONTAINDOESNOTCONTAIN:!~].

h3. Problem Definition 

When switching database to MySQL per [Connecting JIRA applications to MySQL|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver070/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-749382640.html/] from H2 or HSQL. User receives:

{code:title=|borderStyle=solid}
You have an error in your dbconfig.xml file. The schema-name="PUBLIC" only works for a field-type-name of "h2" or "hsql"
{code}
In the logs:
{code:title=|borderStyle=solid}
2017-04-05 00:39:15,265 JIRA-Bootstrap ERROR      [c.a.jira.startup.DefaultJiraLauncher] Johnson events present; aborting: [(Event: Level = (EventLevel: error) , Key = (EventType: database) , Desc = <p>You have an error in your dbconfig.xml file. The schema-name="PUBLIC" only works for a field-type-name of "h2" or "hsql". Please refer to the <a href="http://www.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/latest/databases/index.html">JIRA database documentation</a>.</p> , Exception = ]
{code}
And JIRA is not accessable.

Diagnosis:
According to  [Connecting JIRA applications to MySQL|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver070/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-749382640.html/] when switching to MySQL dbconfig.xml does not require this line:
{code:java}
<schema-name>PUBLIC</schema-name>
{code}

h3. Solution

The error in the user interface and logs needs to be more specific and mentions this schema is required for H2, HSQL and Postgres but not MySQL.
This way the user can gete rid of the line and troubleshoot the issue.

h5.Steps to reproduce:
 # Create a user with a certain username (such as {{dave}})
 # Change the user's _username_ to {{dave!}}
 # Add a custom avatar to this user's profile
 # Create a new user with the username {{dave}}
 # After a hard refresh, the avatar for {{dave!}} is broken

The reason is because the {{ViewUserAvatarServlet}} fetches users by {{username}} instead of {{key}}:

{code}
public class ViewUserAvatarServlet extends AbstractAvatarServlet {
    @Override
    protected void defaultDoGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, String ownerId, Long avatarId, Avatar.Size size)
            throws IOException, ServletException {
        final AvatarService avatarService = ComponentAccessor.getAvatarService();
        final ApplicationUser avatarUser = getUserUtil().getUserByName(ownerId);
        final ApplicationUser remoteUser = getAuthenticationContext().getLoggedInUser();

        if (avatarUser != null && remoteUser != null && avatarService.isUsingExternalAvatar(remoteUser, avatarUser)) {
            redirectToExternalAvatar(response, ownerId, size);
            return;
        }

        super.defaultDoGet(request, response, ownerId, avatarId, size);
    }
{code}

h5.Expected Results
The avatar should display correctly.

h5.Actual Results
The avatar is displayed as a broken image. Attempting to navigate to the avatar directly produces a circular redirect error.

h5.Symptoms:

# The original username appears in the {{avatar}} table, and points to the correct avatar. Permissions on the disk are correct for the avatar.
# The original username appears twice in the {{app_user}} table - one row contains the value in {{user_key}} and the other contains the value in {{lower_user_name}}

Example:

{code}
id    user_key lower_user_name 
----- -------- --------------- 
10105 dave     dave!           
10106 ID10106  dave            
{code}

h5.Workaround
You can attempt to remove the value for the {{lower_user_name}} that shares the original username:

# Shut down JIRA
# Perform a database backup
# Delete the row from {{app_user}}
# Start JIRA again

